{"variants":[{"paths":["\/tutorials\/tws\/notifications"],"traits":[{"interfaceLanguage":"swift"}]}],"identifier":{"interfaceLanguage":"swift","url":"doc:\/\/tws-ios.TWS\/tutorials\/TWS\/Notifications"},"metadata":{"categoryPathComponent":"Tutorial-Table-of-Contents","category":"Learn to use the SDK","role":"project","title":"Integrating TWSNotifications with your notifications"},"sections":[{"kind":"hero","estimatedTimeInMinutes":3,"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"In this tutorial you will learn how to easily integrate TWSNotifications in your existing push notification code base.","type":"text"}]}],"chapter":"Display your first snippet","title":"Integrating TWSNotifications with your notifications"},{"kind":"tasks","tasks":[{"stepsSection":[{"type":"step","media":null,"runtimePreview":null,"code":"Notifications_00.swift","content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Integration of TWSNotifications is very easy. Wherever your app receives a notification, just pass the data to","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"handleTWSPushNotification(userInfo:) method like so.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}],"caption":[{"type":"aside","style":"note","content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"By the time notification is processed by this method, the TWSManager holding the snippet should already be alive.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}],"name":"Note"}]},{"type":"step","media":null,"runtimePreview":null,"code":"Notifications.json","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Notification data should include two keys “type” and “path”. If they are not include handleTWSPushNotification(userInfo:) will ignore the notification.","type":"text"}]}],"caption":[{"type":"aside","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"projectId and snippetId should be replaced with actual ids, again this will work correctly if the TWSManager with the same projectId configuration already exists."}]}],"name":"Note","style":"note"}]},{"type":"step","media":null,"runtimePreview":null,"code":"Notifications_01.swift","content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"As noted in first step TWSManager needs to be alive when push notification is handled. This usually means that the instance should be created before registering @UIApplicationDelegate"}],"type":"paragraph"}],"caption":[]}],"contentSection":[{"kind":"contentAndMedia","mediaPosition":"trailing","content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"This section teaches you how to structure and integrate TWSNotifications, to leverage push notifications even more."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"TWSNotifications is a mechanism that allows you to parse a notification content and display a full screen overlay of the corresponding snippet.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"This tutorial assumes you are already have working push notifications implementation.","type":"text"}]}],"name":"Note","style":"note","type":"aside"}]}],"title":"Integrating TWSNotifications","anchor":"Integrating-TWSNotifications"}]},{"action":{"overridingTitleInlineContent":[{"text":"Get started","type":"text"}],"identifier":"doc:\/\/tws-ios.TWS\/tutorials\/TWS\/CustomizingViews","type":"reference","isActive":true,"overridingTitle":"Get started"},"kind":"callToAction","featuredEyebrow":"Tutorial","abstract":[{"text":"Learn how to customize your view to fit your applications profile.","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"Customize loading, preloading and error views.","type":"text"}],"title":"Customize views to fit your application"}],"schemaVersion":{"major":0,"patch":0,"minor":3},"hierarchy":{"paths":[["doc:\/\/tws-ios.TWS\/tutorials\/Tutorial-Table-of-Contents","doc:\/\/tws-ios.TWS\/tutorials\/Tutorial-Table-of-Contents\/$volume","doc:\/\/tws-ios.TWS\/tutorials\/Tutorial-Table-of-Contents\/Display-your-first-snippet"]],"reference":"doc:\/\/tws-ios.TWS\/tutorials\/Tutorial-Tabl